{
  "doc_id": "59074",
  "text": "Overexpression of Tollip impairs IL-1RI-, TLR2-, and TLR4-triggered NF-B and JNK signaling pathways [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Tollip is a small protein containing an internal C2 domain and a C-terminal CUE domain that was identified in a twohybrid screen using the cytoplasmic tail of IL-1R accessory protein (IL-1RAcP) as bait [CITATION_5] . Tollip binds the activated IL-1RI complex, as well as TLR2 and TLR4 complexes [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Tollip also interacts with IL-1R-associated kinase 1 (IRAK-1) prior to stimulation and suppresses IRAK-1's kinase activity [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . This has led to the concept that a Tollip-mediated pathway is required to maintain immune cells in a quiescent state in the absence of infection and facilitate the termination of IL-1R-and TLR-induced signaling during inflammation via suppression of IRAK-1's activity [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] .",
